```javascript
if (chunk.lastIndexOf('\n') === -1) return;
```

The mutated code has:
```javascript
if (chunk.lastIndexOf("") === -1) return;
```

The key difference: `String.prototype.lastIndexOf("")` always returns the length of the string (never -1), while `lastIndexOf('\n')` returns -1 when there's no newline in the chunk.

The original code is an optimization: if a chunk has no newline, skip processing (since we can't form complete rows yet). The mutated code will always return early (since `lastIndexOf("")` is never -1), meaning data will never be processed from the read stream.

So with the mutation, loading data from a file will fail - the database will appear empty even when the file has data.

